{INTRODUCTION Being a long-time devotee of the Sicilian Defense, I began
studying the Ruy Lopez at a relatively late stage of my career as a
grandmaster. My initial concentration was on popular variations of the main 3..
.a6 Ruy Lopez, such as the Chigorin. I have played both the Breyer and the
Zaitsev while looking in the meantime after earlier deviations, including on
the move 3. Naturally, the trendy Berlin variation did not escape my attention.
Indeed, the other minor opening lines have not been underestimated. In this
selection, I have decided to examine a rare one with 3/\Bc5, which has
practically never been tested (although it is likely to transpose through
various move orders) at the highest level. It also intersects with the
excellent database of Marin/^s, where he suggests going firstly 3...a6 and
only then 4...Bc5 (which is quite popular nowadays) , but at the same time I
am giving completely different options in many directions.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
3. Bb5 Bc5 $5 ({Trendy is} 3... a6 4. Ba4 Bc5 {The main difference of my
database to Marin's is revealed after} 5. c3 ({also, after} 5. O-O d6 6. c3 Bd7
7. d4 Ba7 {transposes to my line, while there is no alternative option 5...
Nd4? because of the simple 6.N:e5+/-}) 5... Nge7 {Here White has two important
options to fight for an advantage:} ({Despite the similarity of my database
with Marin's, nuances are critical in many occasions. For example, after} 5...
Nf6 $6 {with the insertion of moves is just a bad version - after} 6. d4 exd4
7. e5 {it is no longer possible to play} Nd5 $2 8. O-O Be7 9. cxd4 d6 {because
of the crucial} 10. Qb3 $1 {and Black lacks the solid 10...Be6 in the view of
the hanging b7-pawn, which is not the case with the bishop still on the
b5-square.} Nb6 11. d5 Nxa4 12. Qxa4 b5 13. Qe4 $1 Nb8 14. Bg5 (14. exd6 $1 {
was even stronger} cxd6 15. Re1 Nd7 16. Nd4 Nf6 17. Qf3 Bd7 18. Nc6 Bxc6 19.
dxc6 O-O 20. Nc3 $18 {with decisive positional advantage}) 14... h6 15. Bxe7
Qxe7 16. Nbd2 O-O 17. Rac1 $16 {C. Koch - M. Crnic, IECG email, 1999.}) 6. d4 (
{in case of} 6. O-O Ba7 (6... d6 7. d4 Ba7 8. dxe5 $16) 7. d4 {Black has to
direct the knight to g6 very early -} Ng6 {where, according to me, it is not
so flexible. In my line I prefer the set-up with d6, Bd7, when Black is not
prematurely determined the location of his Ne7}) 6... exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ {
where White has decent chances to get a long-term advantage after both} 8. Bd2
({and} 8. Nc3)) 4. c3 ({To} 4. O-O {Black can delay the development of Ng8 in
favour of} d6 ({or} 4... Nd4 $5)) 4... Nf6 $1 (4... Nge7 5. O-O Ng6 6. d4 Bb6 {
is also an option, though the second player may prefer to insert a7-a6 and to
have a bishop respectively on the safer a7-square.}) 5. O-O O-O 6. d4 Bb6 {
is a key tabiya, which will be the subject of Chapter 1.} *

