{[%evp 0,38,29,40,40,40,18,28,21,-1,59,-6,6,-4,8,8,17,3,15,3,3,3,7,-2,6,6,6,6,
12,17,12,12,12,12,12,12,12,0,0,0,8]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6
5. d3 d6 $5 {Nowadays the plans with d7-d5 (immediately or after castling)
considered as the main way to prove an equality. But I have decided to stick
to the good old d7-d6, which is not so forced.} 6. O-O (6. d4 $5 {has recently
become popular -} exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Bd2 {Now it also looks very similar to
the lines from Chapter 2, but it turns out that the extra tempo d7-d6 has not
only pros, for instance Black cannot take on e4 now.} ({it's funny that after} 
8. Kf1 {[%emt 0:00:02] transposes to the same Chapter -} d5 $1 9. e5 Ne4 10.
Qa4 a5 $5 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Qxc6+ Qd7 $1 {with, as we already know, plenty of
counterplay}) 8... O-O $1 ({indeed,} 8... Nxe4 $4 {is terrible blunder -} 9.
Bxb4 $18) ({the more routine} 8... Bxd2+ $6 {is inaccurate -} 9. Nbxd2 Bd7 10.
O-O O-O 11. Re1 Re8 12. h3 Ne7 13. Bf1 c6 14. Qb3 Qb6 15. Qa3 $16 {Giri -
Radjabov, Stavanger, 2022}) 9. Bxc6 (9. Bxb4 Nxb4 10. Nc3 (10. a3 Nc6 11. d5
Ne7 12. Nc3 c6 $11) {Now Black has a decent choice -} 10... Bg4 (10... a6 $5
11. Be2 Re8 12. a3 Nc6 13. d5 Na7 $5 14. Qc2 Nb5 $132) 11. a3 Bxf3 12. gxf3 c6
13. Ba4 (13. Be2 Na6 14. h4 Nc7 $132) 13... b5 $5 {since White's king will be
permanently unsafe. Black is ready to sac one pawn and sometimes even two -}
14. Bb3 (14. axb4 bxa4 15. Qxa4 Qc8 $44) (14. Bxb5 Nbd5 $5 15. Bxc6 Nxc3 16.
bxc3 Rb8 17. Qd2 Nh5 $44) 14... Na6 15. Qd2 Rb8 16. Rg1 g6 $132) 9... Bxd2+ 10.
Nbxd2 bxc6 11. O-O {White's pawn structure is better and his chances are,
therefore slightly higher.} Re8 (11... Nh5 $5 {- as well as in other Chapters
the main counterplay is connected with f7-f5}) 12. Re1 a5 (12... Nh5 13. Nf1
$14) 13. Qc2 Bd7 14. b3 (14. Nf1) 14... h6 15. a4 {So far Fressinet - Bacrot,
Agen, 2017, Black must once again consider} Nh5 $5 $132) 6... O-O (6... Bb6 {
This relatively rare move order has no drawbacks in my opinion. The main idea
is to postpone the short castle for one move to neutralize the aggressive plan
with Bc1-g5. If White is trying to play in the pure positional manner by
gradually preparing to push d3-d4, then Black is normally ready to meet his
intentions with the relevant d6-d5 just in time.} 7. Bg5 ({In reply to} 7. Nbd2
O-O 8. Nc4 {Black can start the typical manoeuvre} Ne7 9. Ba4 {An interesting
try to hide the bishop before the exchange of ?b6.} (9. Re1 Ng4 {/\f5?}) ({
indeed, it is possible to insert} 9. Nxb6 axb6 {before} 10. Ba4 {with mutual
chances after} Ng6 11. h3 d5 $5 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Re1 $140 Ndf4 14. Bxf4 Nxf4
15. Bc2 Ra5) 9... Ng6 (9... h6 {is possible, though far from necessary here})
10. Nxb6 axb6 11. Bc2 b5 12. h3 c5 13. d4 Be6 {and in case of} 14. d5 Bd7 {
Black has a very nice version of Indian pawn structure}) (7. h3 O-O 8. Bg5 h6
9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Nh5 11. Bh2 g4 $36) ({if} 7. Na3 O-O 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 {
Black can bet on} g5 10. Bg3 Ne7 11. Nc4 Ng6) ({so is with} 7. Re1 O-O 8. Bg5
h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Ne7 11. d4 Ng6 $132) 7... h6 8. Bh4 Bg4 9. Nbd2 g5 {
Without castling Black has more room for a counterplay -} 10. Bg3 Nh5 11. Nc4 (
11. Re1 Nxg3 12. hxg3 h5 {/\h4}) (11. Kh1 Qf6 12. h3 Bd7) 11... Qf6 12. d4 Bxf3
13. gxf3 {This wrecked pawn structure always reminds me of the famous game
Winter-Capablanca, where the bishop on g3 was shut down until the end of the
game. In our case White has more dynamic opportunities and the position
remains very tense. Now Black has a narrow choice -} Nxg3 (13... exd4 $6 14. e5
$36) 14. hxg3 {and here very messy, although quite playable is} exd4 15. a4 $1
(15. e5 $6 dxe5 16. Nxe5 O-O-O $1 $17) 15... O-O 16. a5 ({in the current
position Black does not have time to stop the march of the a-pawn anymore, but
} 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. a5 {does not win a piece because of} Bc5 18. b4 d5) 16...
Nxa5 17. Nxa5 dxc3 18. Nc4 cxb2 19. Rb1 Bd4 20. Ba4 (20. Ne3 Bxe3 21. fxe3 Qe5
{is likely to finish in a draw by repetition}) 20... c6 21. Bc2 b5 22. Ne3 Bxe3
23. fxe3 a5 {White will have to exchange the queens in order to get rid of the
b2-pawn, but even without it the phalanx seems frightening}) 7. Nbd2 (7. h3 Ne7
{The typical knight transfer to the kingside, known from the Italian game.} 8.
d4 (8. Re1 c6 9. Ba4 Ng6 10. Nbd2 Bb6 11. Nf1 d5 {Black has been the first to
advance in the center and is fine -} 12. exd5 (12. Ng3 Be6 13. Bc2 Re8 14. exd5
Bxd5 15. c4 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Nh4 $15 {Hostinsky - Galliano, ICCF email, 2018})
12... Nxd5 13. d4 (13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Rxe5 Bxf2+ 15. Kxf2 Qf6+) 13... exd4 14.
Nxd4 Qc7 $132 15. Bb3 $140 Ndf4) 8... Bb6 9. Re1 (9. Nbd2 c6 10. Ba4 Ng6) 9...
d5 $1 {is well-known strike, which is considered by the theory to solve the
opening problems.} (9... c6 10. Bd3 Ng6 11. Nbd2 {- this is what Black tries
to avoid}) 10. Nxe5 Nxe4 11. Nd2 Nd6 12. Bd3 f6 13. Nef3 Bf5 14. Nf1 (14. Nb3
Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Ng6 16. h4 Re8 17. h5 Rxe1+ 18. Nxe1 Qe8 19. Nc2 Nf8 20. a4 a5
21. Bf4 Ne4 22. Qf3 Ne6 23. Bh2 Rd8 {was roughly equal in Nekhaev - V.
Grigoryev, ICCF email, 2019, as well}) 14... Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Qd7 16. Bf4 Rae8 17.
Ng3 Nef5 18. Bxd6 Nxd6 $11 {Le Quang - Cheparinov, Hengshui, 2019}) 7... Bd7 8.
Nc4 Bb6 9. Nxb6 axb6 10. Re1 Ne7 {The position is approximately equal without
the pair of bishops.} 11. Bxd7 ({Or} 11. Bc4 Ba4 $5 {(a curious way to provoke
a bishop exchange)} 12. b3 Bc6 13. d4 Nxe4 14. dxe5 d5 ({Black should not have
locked her bishop, for example} 14... Nxc3 15. Qc2 Bxf3 16. exd6 Qxd6 17. Qxc3
Bc6 18. Bb2 Qg6 19. Qxg7+ Qxg7 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 21. Rxe7 {looks precarious for
Black, but} b5 {with ?c6-d5 next will most probably clean the queenside, thus
creating sufficient counterchances}) ({fully playable is also} 14... Ng6 {
- Black has active pieces and just enough counterplay after} 15. exd6 Qxd6 16.
Qc2 Rfe8 17. Be3 Qf6 18. Nd4 Nd6 19. Bf1 Bd7 20. Rad1 Nh4) 15. Bd3 Ng6 16. Qc2
$14 Re8 17. c4 Nc5 18. Bg5 {Black is facing concrete problems and the bizarre
retreat} Qb8 $2 {has been penalized on the spot by} 19. Bxg6 hxg6 20. b4 Ba4
21. Qd2 Ne4 22. Qxd5 Bc6 23. Qd4 $18 Nxg5 24. Nxg5 Qd8 25. Qh4 Qd3 26. e6 Kf8
27. e7+ {1-0 A. Muzychuk - P. Guichard, Monaco, 2019.}) 11... Qxd7 12. Bg5 Qe6
13. d4 Ng6 14. d5 Qe7 15. Nh4 h6 ({Black is reasonably eliminating the pin,
even though} 15... Nxh4 16. Bxh4 h6 {and g7-g5, when necessary, seems reliable
as well. e. g.} 17. f3 b5 18. a3 c6 $132) 16. Nf5 Qd8 17. Bd2 Ne7 18. Qf3 Nxf5
19. Qxf5 Qd7 $11 {D. Faerber - O. Stork, Hannover, 2015. White has once again
to reckon with the f7-f5 break.} *

